I have defined several layouts, where few id's are multiple defined. I am confused how does it work? why doesn't it give error just like we get in java code?

This is because Android's resource IDs are unique within their respective scopes. If you have the same ID in two different XML files, the system will automatically append a number to the end of the ID to make it unique. For instance, if you have an ID "image1" in two XML files, the system will generate R.id.image1 and R.id.image1_1 in the R.java file.

and most importantly, how does environment decide to which component it needs to invoke?

The environment uses the resource IDs to find the corresponding view in the current view hierarchy. When you call findViewById(), it searches the current view hierarchy for a view that has the specified resource ID. If it finds a match, it returns that view. If it doesn't find a match, it returns null.

In case we have to use 2 XMLs in an Activity, one as activity.setcontentview(layout1) and another as a PopupWindow.setContentView(layout2). What will happen in such case?

If you call setContentView() on an Activity with a different layout XML file, the system will replace the current view hierarchy with the new layout. This means that any views that were previously found using findViewById() will no longer point to the same views.

How can I write ArrayList Adapter?:

To create an ArrayList Adapter, you need to create a custom ArrayAdapter class that extends the ArrayAdapter class. This class will be responsible for converting the data in your ArrayList into views that can be displayed in a ListView.

Here is a basic example of how you might create an ArrayList Adapter for your Income class:

```java
public class IncomeAdapter extends ArrayAdapter<Income> {
    public IncomeAdapter(Context context, ArrayList<Income> incomes) {
        super(context, 0, incomes);
    }

    @Override
    public View getView(int position, View convertView, ViewGroup parent) {
        Income income = getItem(position);

        if (convertView == null) {
            convertView = LayoutInflater.from(getContext()).inflate(R.layout.income_item, parent, false);
        }

        TextView kalemTextView = convertView.findViewById(R.id.kalem_text_view);
        TextView tutarTextView = convertView.findViewById(R.id.tutar_text_view);

        kalemTextView.setText(income.getKalem());
        tutarTextView.setText(String.valueOf(income.getTutar()));

        return convertView;
    }
}
```

In this example, `income_item.xml` is a layout file that represents a single item in the ListView. You would replace `R.layout.income_item` with the resource ID of your own layout file. The `kalem_text_view` and `tutar_text_view` are also resource IDs that you would replace with the actual IDs of the TextViews in your layout file.

You would then use this adapter in your Activity like this:

```java
ArrayList<Income> incomes = helper.getAllIncome();
IncomeAdapter adapter = new IncomeAdapter(this, incomes);
ListView listView = findViewById(R.id.list_view);
listView.setAdapter(adapter);
```

In this example, `list_view` is the resource ID of your ListView. You would replace `R.id.list_view` with the actual ID of your ListView.

